  "prompt": "Buying life insurance at age 60. What should I be careful for?",
  "response": "When considering life insurance at age 60, there are several important factors to keep in mind to ensure you make the right choice for your circumstances:\n\n1. **Type of Policy**: Understand the different types of life insurance available (term life, whole life, universal life, etc.) and determine which aligns with your needs and goals. Term life insurance is often less expensive but only lasts for a specified term, while whole life provides coverage for your entire life but can be significantly more costly.\n\n2. **Health Considerations**: Your health will significantly impact your eligibility and premiums for life insurance. Be prepared for a medical exam and have your medical history available. Pre-existing health conditions may result in higher premiums or denial of coverage.\n\n3. **Premium Costs**: Insurance premiums generally increase with age. Get quotes from multiple insurers to compare costs, and consider how much you can afford to pay monthly or annually.\n\n4. **Coverage Amount**: Determine how much coverage you need based on your financial responsibilities, such as debts, mortgage, education costs for dependents, and potential funeral expenses. \n\n5. **Beneficiaries**: Decide who you want to name as beneficiaries and ensure their information is updated. Consider the financial needs of your beneficiaries at the time of your passing.\n\n6. **Policy Terms and Conditions**: Carefully read the policy details, including any exclusions, waiting periods, and renewal options. Understand what might cause the policy to lapse and how to reinstate it if needed.\n\n7. **Riders and Add-ons**: Look into policies that offer riders (additional benefits) that might be relevant, such as accelerated death benefits in case of terminal illness, accidental death coverage, or chronic illness riders.\n\n8. **Company Reputation**: Research the insurance company\u2019s financial stability, customer service reputation, and claims settlement history. You want to choose a reliable insurer.\n\n9. **Long-term Needs**: Consider any potential future needs or changes in circumstance. For instance, if you plan to retire soon or have a change in dependents, this might affect the type and amount of insurance you need.\n\n10. **Tax Implications**: Generally, life insurance death benefits are tax-free to beneficiaries, but consider speaking to a financial advisor about any tax implications for your estate.\n\n11. **Review Regularly**: Life changes such as marriage, divorce, or the birth of grandchildren may necessitate policy adjustments. Regularly review your life insurance needs and adjust your policy accordingly.\n\nGiven your age and potential changes in health and financial requirements, it may also be wise to consult with a financial advisor or insurance professional to make informed decisions tailored to your specific situation.",
